e) The emergency response program

The Emergency Response Program requirements for Program 1 Facilities are very similar to those required under the PSM rule. The Emergency Response Program required under the RMP and PSM Rules must be site-specific and comprehensive, including the following elements: 



?Public and emergency response agency notification procedures;

?Proper first aid and emergency medical treatment;

?Emergency response measures;

?Procedures for inspecting, testing, and maintaining emergency response equipment;

?Employee training; and

?Program review procedures.



EnLink maintains a corporate Emergency Preparedness and Response Plan (EPRP) that provides guidance for emergencies expected at all EnLink facilities, including Upper Hill, as well as additional safety information. Upper Hill also maintains a site-specific Emergency Action Plan. In addition, operating procedures and equipment design codes and standards associated with the operations at the Facility are maintained. Furthermore, the Facility has coordinated the emergency response with the local fire department. For these reasons, Upper Hill meets the exceptions listed in 40 CFR 68.90(b), and therefore the Facility is not required to have the Emergency Response Program as described in 40 CFR 68.95. As such, the Facility is non responsive.





f) Planned changes to improve safety

The Facility last completed a Process Hazard Analysis (PHA) during design of the Facility in 2013 to assess potential areas to improve safety at the Facility. The final action item from the PHA was completed before startup. Pre-startup safety reviews (PSSRs) are conducted on a regular basis whenever changes are made to the process. The Facility will update and revalidate the PHA every 5 years as per OSHA PSM and EPA RMP regulations.
